<TITLE> Govt opens talks with Russia on N-power </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Maruf Mallick bdnews24.com energy correspondent Dhaka, Mar 31 (bdnews24.com)Bangladesh started talks with Russian experts in Dhaka Tuesday to set up a nuclear power plant. A two-strong high-level delegation led by Vladimir Averkiev, head of international co-operation of Russian State Atomic Energy Corporation, arrived in the capital on Monday night. Nikolay Poznyakov, head of external affairs of International Relations Department, was the other delegate. They said Bangladesh could generate 2000 megawatts of electricity from the plant by 2017. At least 1000 MW by 2016, said a high official of the science and ICT ministry, who attended the meeting but wanted to remain unnamed. The Russian team highlighted the technical aspects of a 1000-MW power plant, sources close to the negotiations said. The head of Bangladesh delegation, joint secretary M M Neazuddin, told bdnews24.com the Russians masde a presentation and the government would brief them on the situation Wednesday. "We have the infrastructure, however some laws related to nuclear power should be updated," he added.</TEXT>
